1st October 1949,

116
00:04:51,637 --> 00:04:54,403
People's Republic of China was born.

117
00:04:54,403 --> 00:04:55,974
"The leader of the Communists,

118
00:04:55,974 --> 00:04:57,548
and the hero of the revolution,

119
00:04:57,548 --> 00:04:58,818
is Mao Zedong."

120
00:05:09,278 --> 00:05:12,162
In 1958, Mao launched

121
00:05:12,162 --> 00:05:14,671
the Great Leap Forward Campaign.

122
00:05:14,671 --> 00:05:16,953
Its aim was to bring economic

123
00:05:16,953 --> 00:05:18,973
and social transformation to the country.

124
00:05:18,973 --> 00:05:20,227
There were two main policies in this.

125
00:05:20,227 --> 00:05:23,053
First, to take the land from the landowners

126
00:05:23,053 --> 00:05:24,635
and distribute it among the farmers.

127
00:05:24,635 --> 00:05:26,073
Land redistribution.

128
00:05:26,073 --> 00:05:29,351
Thereafter, collectivizing agriculture.

129
00:05:29,351 --> 00:05:31,369
Agricultural cooperatives were made so that

130
00:05:31,369 --> 00:05:33,797
more farmers could work on the same land.

131
00:05:33,797 --> 00:05:35,878
But ultimately, the ownership of the land

132
00:05:35,878 --> 00:05:37,453
was in the hands of the government.

133
00:05:37,453 --> 00:05:39,238
Second, industrialization.

134
00:05:39,238 --> 00:05:42,323
On the one hand, large industrial plants were built for steel production.

135
00:05:42,323 --> 00:05:44,940
And on the other hand,
telling people to make

136
00:05:44,940 --> 00:05:48,461
small-scale steel furnaces in their backyards

137
00:05:48,461 --> 00:05:50,533
to produce steel at a local level.

138
00:05:50,533 --> 00:05:51,729
The intention was good.

139
00:05:51,729 --> 00:05:53,604
To develop the country economically.

140
00:05:53,604 --> 00:05:55,563
But the result was very bad.

141
00:05:55,563 --> 00:05:59,912
The small-scale steel furnaces that people had built in their gardens

142
00:05:59,912 --> 00:06:03,474
were producing low-quality steel.

143
00:06:03,474 --> 00:06:05,085
This led to the resources being wasted.

144
00:06:05,085 --> 00:06:06,653
Secondly, the farmers did not have

145
00:06:06,653 --> 00:06:08,745
any incentive to increase their production

146
00:06:08,745 --> 00:06:10,228
because there was no profit sharing

147
00:06:10,228 --> 00:06:12,087
and no private ownership.

148
00:06:12,087 --> 00:06:13,256
The ownership of the land was ultimately

149
00:06:13,256 --> 00:06:14,941
in the hands of the government.

150
00:06:14,941 --> 00:06:17,166
So, whatever crop was being grown by the farmers,

151
00:06:17,166 --> 00:06:18,356
had to be handed over to the government.

152
00:06:18,356 --> 00:06:21,122
This led to a huge decline in productivity.

153
00:06:21,122 --> 00:06:23,003
Between 1958 and 1961,

154
00:06:23,003 --> 00:06:25,436
the grain production fell by 15%.

155
00:06:25,436 --> 00:06:27,775
In just a few years,
due to bad weather and

156
00:06:27,775 --> 00:06:30,343
some other “masterstroke” policies of
the Mao regime,

157
00:06:30,343 --> 00:06:34,225
the situation got so bad that
the whole country was starving.

158
00:06:34,225 --> 00:06:35,944
The famine was so terrible that

159
00:06:35,944 --> 00:06:40,102
around 20-40 million people died in this famine in China.

160
00:06:40,102 --> 00:06:42,989
It is known as one of the deadliest famines
in history.

161
00:06:42,989 --> 00:06:46,005
To put it bluntly,
Mao Zedong was a dictator.

162
00:06:46,005 --> 00:06:49,902
And because there is no
checks and balances system for dictators,

163
00:06:49,902 --> 00:06:51,702
as there is in a democracy,

164
00:06:51,702 --> 00:06:53,721
dictators often have a habit of

165
00:06:53,721 --> 00:06:57,785
imposing their wills without thinking or testing.

166
00:06:57,785 --> 00:07:02,104
Several such decisions by Mao
made China worse.

167
00:07:02,104 --> 00:07:04,128
Another example of such decisions

168
00:07:04,128 --> 00:07:05,828
was the Sparrow Extermination.

169
00:07:05,828 --> 00:07:08,162
Mao's intention was to
increase food production.

170
00:07:08,162 --> 00:07:10,435
So, it was ordered that all the sparrows,

171
00:07:10,435 --> 00:07:12,459
and all the birds should be killed

172
00:07:12,459 --> 00:07:14,843
because those birds ate the grains.

173
00:07:14,843 --> 00:07:17,029
They eat some crop grains from the fields.

174
00:07:17,029 --> 00:07:19,269
So, the crops are affected by the crops,

175
00:07:19,269 --> 00:07:21,317
so all the birds in the country were to be exterminated.

176
00:07:21,317 --> 00:07:23,915
When this campaign was run,
and sparrows were killed,

177
00:07:23,915 --> 00:07:25,487
a few years later, people realised that

178
00:07:25,487 --> 00:07:29,291
the insects and pests were multiplying so rapidly

179
00:07:29,291 --> 00:07:31,538
they were causing more damage to the crops.

180
00:07:31,538 --> 00:07:34,520
This worsened the food shortage.

181
00:07:34,520 --> 00:07:39,063
Later, a scientist found that if all the birds are killed,

182
00:07:39,063 --> 00:07:41,752
then no one would be left to eat those insects.

183
00:07:41,752 --> 00:07:43,775
The birds used to eat the insects

184
00:07:43,775 --> 00:07:45,986
which kept the insect population in control.

185
00:07:45,986 --> 00:07:48,878
The entire ecological balance was disturbed.

186
00:07:48,878 --> 00:07:50,879
And the situation worsened so terribly
that it led to a famine.

187
00:07:50,879 --> 00:07:54,074
After such a big failure, Mao was criticized

188
00:07:54,074 --> 00:07:57,202
by the Chinese public and by the Communist Party too.

189
00:07:57,202 --> 00:08:00,284
But Mao Zedong was not willing to admit his mistake.

190
00:08:00,284 --> 00:08:02,314
Another campaign was started.

191
00:08:02,314 --> 00:08:05,164
Cultural Revolution in 1966.

192
00:08:05,164 --> 00:08:07,486
The name suggests that it was meant to

193
00:08:07,486 --> 00:08:09,028
bring a revolution of culture in the country

194
00:08:09,028 --> 00:08:10,800
but the real purpose was

195
00:08:10,800 --> 00:08:14,030
to give control to Mao
and suppress the opposition.

196
00:08:14,030 --> 00:08:17,558
Propaganda and PR machinery
were used extensively here.

197
